```
random but I go here:  <https://www.makeschool.com/>
It's pretty cool. We're really diverse and queer. We have a queer club that ~1/4 of the school is in. My CS teacher has a rainbow mohawk. The academic compliance officer plays D&D with us and uses they/them. Overall would recommend if you like coding and would be down to move to SF.
I'll be a senior next year so if you get admitted for fall I'll still be there! Some of the seniors from this year already got jobs at places like Google and NASA.
Oh and btw you can use my referral link and I think they'll look at your application first or something.
```

attachments.text: Bring an idea to life with ambitious people just like you! Learn what it takes to build a startup, meet investors, and join a community of aspiring female & non-binary founders.Violet Hacks is a 2-day startup-focused hackathon for female & non-binary individuals in technology. Never been to a hackathon before? Not even sure what they are? No sweat!Get ready for an awesome weekend of creating, learning, and connecting. You'll work on a team with 4-5 other talented techies who have a variety of roles & backgrounds — Engineering, Design, Product, Marketing, Biz Dev, Talent, Community, Success, and more — who want to start a startup. There will be workshops, talks, and resources to help you put together a brand-new business concept, prototype, and pitch. You'll have delicious meals and fun swag included in admission. Finally, on Sunday you'll demo your creations to a panel of judges (accomplished investors & founders) and compete to win awesome prizes! Thank you our generous host & partner, Domino Data Lab, for providing our venue!Our judges are accomplished founders & investors:- Selene Cruz, Founder & CEO at RE:STORE- Amy Sun, Partner at Sequoia Capital- Harshita Arora, Founder of Crypto Price Tracker (acquired by Redwood City Ventures)- Morgan Lai, Investor at Foundation Capital- Sampriti Bhattacharyya, Founder of Hydroswarm- Jennifer Kaehms, Investment Associate at Canvas Ventures - Ellen Chisa, CEO/Cofounder of Dark Inc- Kinjal Shah, Investment Associate at Blockchain Capital LLC- Charu Sharma, CEO of Next PlayStay tuned for more announcements of workshop leaders, speakers, and more. FAQ:- Your ticket includes connections to dozens of companies, 10+ founders and investors, 5 meals plus snacks, 4-6 workshops, and potential for prizes worth hundreds of dollars!- The event will be Saturday, Nov 3 from 10am-10pm and Sunday, Nov 4 from 10am-3pm. No overnight stay is allowed in Domino Data Lab.- This is an 18+ event, no minors will be allowed, sorry!- No travel reimbursement is available; if you'll be coming from out of town, please arrange your own overnight stay- Attendees must be female or non-binary.- Terms of Participation: <https://docs.google.com/document/d/1y_Nss-eO5psGO8qqp3UDf4kbrJNh3rfNTkYYAUnGCx0/edit?usp=sharing> Violet Hacks is run by The Violet Society, a startup sisterhood for future founders. We run high-touch, face-to-face programs for ambitious women in the first 10 years of their career who are aspiring and early-stage founders. The Violet Society gives members the confidence and skills they need to launch and grow a successful startup. Learn more about upcoming events, subscribe to our email list, and follow us on social media via our website: <http://thevioletsociety.com/>

attachments.title: National Coming Out Day
attachments.text: National Coming Out Day (NCOD) is an annual LGBT awareness day observed on October 11 and 12 in some parts of the world. Founded in the United States in 1988, the initial idea was grounded in the feminist and gay liberation spirit of the personal being political, and the emphasis on the most basic form of activism being coming out to family, friends and colleagues, and living life as an openly lesbian or gay person. They believe the foundational belief is that homophobia thrives in an atmosphere of silence and ignorance, and that once people know that they have loved ones who are lesbian or gay, they are far less likely to maintain homophobic or oppressive <http://views.In|views.In> more recent years, the idea of the "lesbian and gay community" has been largely subsumed into the idea of the LGBT community, and the idea of "coming out" expanded to include not only the voluntary self-disclosure of a lesbian, gay, or bisexual sexual orientation,  but also that of transgender, genderqueer, or other non-mainstream gender identity.
